thick wire-wrapped ropes corners~
Four thick lines of heavy rope hang down from the vertical shaft in which
this platform dangles.  Each rope is three inches across, and wrapped in
a protective sheath of intertwined wire strands along its length. 
Numerous portions of the wire wrapping have snapped, their pointy edges
jutting forth in minute lengths.  Where the wire has snapped, individual
strands of rope have frayed, but looks like it will still hold up the
platform with ease.
~
E
set wrought-iron gates west~
Supported on both sides of the west rock face by metal tracks bolted to
its surface, a set of intricate wrought-iron gates hang to prevent the
foolhardy from falling to their deaths when the lift is not present on
that level.  What once have been a dazzling array of metalworking has
been reduced to a jumble of intersected rods, as most of the individual
tips of metal have been broken off, more than likely used to forge new
weapons or armor by scavengers.
~
E
heavily rusted old machinery gaps~
A complex set of pistons and gears is partially visible sticking out from
gaps cut into the rock face in the western corners of the vertical shaft.
Apparently a mechanism for opening and closing the wrought-iron gates
that protect bumbling passersby from falling into the lifter shaft.  Most
of the machinery has thick layers of rust covering its surface, almost
completely through the metal in some portions.  Long scratches on some
gears indicate some attempt at maintenance has taken place since the
lifter was built, though from the looks of things it could all fall apart
at any moment.
